---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="System Prompt">
  <main class="main-content" style="width:100%">
    <div class="apa-paper">
      <div class="running-head">
        <span>SYSTEM PROMPT DOCUMENTATION</span>
        <span class="page-num">1</span>
      </div>
      <div class="apa-content">
        <h1>AI System Prompt: Constructing an Astro Textbook Website</h1>
        <p class="no-indent" style="text-align:center; font-style:italic">OpenTextbook Project Documentation</p>

        <div class="abstract">
          <h2>Abstract</h2>
          <p>
            This document presents the system prompt used to instruct an AI coding assistant to
            build and redesign a complete academic textbook website using Astro, Tailwind CSS, and
            TypeScript. The prompt specifies a file-driven content architecture, a chapter-focused
            navigation design, visual design conventions, and technical implementation details
            necessary to produce a functional, production-ready static site.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>
          The following prompt was provided to an AI assistant (GitHub Copilot) to redesign a
          full-featured open textbook website. The site is styled after APA-7 journal articles
          and organizes academic content across a five-level hierarchy: Topics, Books, Units,
          Chapters, and Sections. Sections, subsections, and sub-subsections now live as headings
          within each chapter's Markdown document rather than as separate pages. The prompt is
          reproduced below in full.
        </p>

        <h2>The Prompt</h2>

        <h3>Overview and Goal</h3>
        <p>
          Re-design an existing <strong>Astro.build</strong> textbook website so that the topics,
          books, units, and chapters are represented as a subfolder system under
          <code>src/content/chapters/</code>. Each chapter is a single Markdown document whose
          headings (H2–H4) represent the sections, subsections, and sub-subsections. The site
          must use only two navigation systems: a fluent top navbar for reaching chapters, and a
          left sidebar for navigating within a chapter document.
        </p>

        <h3>Content Architecture</h3>
        <p>
          Organize all chapter content as Markdown files under:
        </p>
        <p class="no-indent" style="font-family:monospace;padding-left:0.5in">
          src/content/chapters/&lt;topic&gt;/&lt;book&gt;/&lt;unit&gt;/&lt;chapter&gt;.md
        </p>
        <p>
          Each chapter file has frontmatter declaring its position in the hierarchy
          (<code>topicSlug</code>, <code>topicTitle</code>, <code>bookSlug</code>,
          <code>bookTitle</code>, <code>unitSlug</code>, <code>unitTitle</code>,
          <code>order</code>) and a Markdown body where H2 = sections, H3 = subsections,
          H4 = sub-subsections. Adding a new chapter requires only creating a new
          <code>.md</code> file; no code changes are needed.
        </p>

        <h3>Navigation Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Implement exactly two navigation systems:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Top navbar (fluent chapter navigation):</strong> A fixed top bar with a
            dropdown per topic that exposes chapters grouped by book and unit. Clicking a chapter
            link navigates directly to that chapter's reading page.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Left sidebar (document navigation):</strong> Visible on the chapter reading
            page. Populated from the headings extracted by Astro's content collection renderer
            (<code>entry.render()</code> returns a <code>headings</code> array). H2 headings are
            top-level sidebar items; H3 and H4 are indented. Active heading is highlighted on
            scroll using an <code>IntersectionObserver</code>.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Remove all section-level route pages. The chapter IS the document.
        </p>

        <h3>Data Layer</h3>
        <p>
          Use Astro Content Collections (defined in <code>src/content/config.ts</code>) with a
          Zod schema for the chapter frontmatter. The <code>src/data/content.ts</code> file
          exports only TypeScript interfaces and helper functions:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>NavChapter</code>, <code>NavUnit</code>, <code>NavBook</code>, <code>NavTopic</code> — navigation tree types</li>
          <li><code>entryToNavChapter(entry)</code> — converts a collection entry to a <code>NavChapter</code></li>
          <li><code>buildNavTree(chapters)</code> — builds the full nested nav tree</li>
          <li><code>getChapterNav(chapters, currentHref)</code> — returns prev/next chapters</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          All data loading at build time occurs in <code>.astro</code> files via
          <code>getCollection('chapters')</code> from <code>astro:content</code>.
        </p>

        <h3>Chapter Reading Page</h3>
        <p>
          The chapter reading page at
          <code>/[topic]/[book]/[unit]/[chapter]</code> includes:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A left sidebar with document-heading navigation</li>
          <li>A main APA-7 formatted "paper" rendering the full chapter Markdown</li>
          <li>Previous/next chapter pagination links at the bottom</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          There is no breadcrumb on the chapter page—the navbar and sidebar provide all necessary
          orientation context.
        </p>

        <h3>Visual Design: APA-7 Journal Article Format</h3>
        <p>
          All chapter content pages visually resemble a LaTeX-generated APA-7 journal article:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Font: Times New Roman or equivalent serif font at 12pt equivalent</li>
          <li>Line spacing: double-spaced</li>
          <li>Margins: 1-inch equivalent on all sides</li>
          <li>Running head in the header (book title in uppercase)</li>
          <li>APA heading levels: H1 centered bold, H2 flush-left bold, H3 flush-left bold italic, H4 indented bold inline</li>
          <li>Paragraphs indented 0.5 inches (except first paragraph after a heading)</li>
          <li>The "paper" rendered as a white card with a shadow on a gray background</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Technical Stack</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Framework:</strong> Astro (latest, static output)</li>
          <li><strong>Styling:</strong> Tailwind CSS via <code>@astrojs/tailwind</code></li>
          <li><strong>Language:</strong> TypeScript (strict mode)</li>
          <li><strong>Content:</strong> Astro Content Collections with Markdown files</li>
          <li><strong>Routing:</strong> File-based with <code>getStaticPaths()</code></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>
          The prompt described above was executed by GitHub Copilot to produce this redesigned
          website. The resulting application is fully file-driven: adding a chapter requires
          only dropping a new <code>.md</code> file into the correct subfolder. The site achieves
          the dual-navigation requirement (top navbar for chapter selection, left sidebar for
          in-document navigation) and maintains the APA-7 visual design throughout.
        </p>

        <h2>References</h2>
        <p class="no-indent" style="padding-left:0.5in;text-indent:-0.5in">
          American Psychological Association. (2020). <em>Publication manual of the American
          Psychological Association</em> (7th ed.). https://doi.org/10.1037/0000165-000
        </p>
        <p class="no-indent" style="padding-left:0.5in;text-indent:-0.5in">
          Astro contributors. (2024). <em>Astro documentation</em>. https://docs.astro.build/
        </p>
        <p class="no-indent" style="padding-left:0.5in;text-indent:-0.5in">
          GitHub. (2024). <em>GitHub Copilot documentation</em>. https://docs.github.com/copilot
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
